I think this is one of the best questions to ask whenever an AI system changes:

“What workflows became possible that weren’t practical before?”

That’s a more durable question than “What changed?” because it focuses on capability rather than implementation.

For Pantheon, here’s where I think the biggest leverage is today.

1. Artifact-first development

This is the most obvious one because we just used it.

Instead of

Conversation
↓
copy manually
↓
rewrite
↓
repo

we can now much more naturally work as

Conversation
↓
canonical doctrine
↓
repository-ready artifact
↓
implementation

That dramatically reduces translation loss.

⸻

2. Better separation of exploration and canon

One thing Pantheon has always wrestled with is:

brainstorming
vs
canonical doctrine

Now it’s much easier to spend time exploring…

…then say

“Formalize this.”

and produce something ready to commit.

That keeps creativity high without polluting the repository.

⸻

3. Larger architectural continuity

Because I can organize larger artifacts more coherently, we can start thinking in terms of:

* doctrine libraries
* operator catalogs
* daemon specifications
* API specs
* game design docs
* research notebooks

instead of isolated conversations.

